polyhooks
=========

This crate is a vendored fork of prek, a fast Git hook manager written in Rust
and designed as a drop-in alternative to pre-commit.

  Upstream project : prek
  Upstream author  : j178 <hi@j178.dev>
  Upstream repo    : https://github.com/j178/prek
  Vendored tag     : v0.4.5
  Vendored commit  : bb3108283fd4aab0d9eb59f23098e0c05a96cdbe
  Upstream license : MIT (SPDX: MIT) — see ./LICENSE

We vendor (rather than depend on a pinned git revision) because we intend to
deeply modify this code: retargeting its configuration from
`.pre-commit-config.yaml` to polylint's `poly.toml`, adding an in-process fast
path, and folding it into the `poly` binary family. This is an intentional
exception to the polylint "no vendoring / pinned-git-dep" rule, which targets
wrapped *library* backends, not a tool we are forking outright.

Changes from upstream in this phase-1 vendoring (behavior-preserving):
  - The upstream Cargo workspace (crates `prek`, `prek-consts`, `prek-identify`,
    `prek-pty`) was flattened into a single crate, `polyhooks`. The three helper
    crates became the public modules `consts`, `identify`, and `pty`
    respectively; cross-crate paths (`prek_consts::`, `prek_identify::`,
    `prek_pty::`) were rewritten to the in-crate equivalents
    (`polyhooks::consts::`, `polyhooks::identify::`, `polyhooks::pty::`).
  - The `serde` cfg gates in the `identify` module were dropped because serde is
    an unconditional dependency here (the binary always enabled it upstream).
  - The binary target is still named `prek` so the vendored integration tests
    and shell-completion snapshots keep working.

Third-party license texts retained from upstream live in ./licenses/.

